853 Fifth Avenue, east side, between 66th and 67th Streets. About 1910.

This is the home of Colonel Olive H. Payne.

The house on the right belongs to H.O. Havemeyer; on left, Benjamin Thaw.
854 Fifth Avenue, east side, between 66th and 67th Streets. About 1910.

Fifth Avenue, east side, at 66th Street.
1922.

Fifth Avenue, East Side, North from East 66th Street. The corner house, the Henry O. Havemeyer Mansion and contiguous to it are the residences of Colonel Oliver H. Payne and Benjamin Thaw.

June, 1925

3-5 East 66th Street, adjoining and east of the N.E. corner of Fifth Avenue. Number 3 East 66th Street will be torn down to make room for an apartment house.

1926.

Brown Brothers.

To those of the Seventh who made the supreme sacrifice.
The 7th Regiment War Memorial at Fifth Avenue and 66th Street was unveiled tbd, the ninth anniversary of the battle of the Hindenburg line and accepted by Mayor Walker as the Regiment's gift to the City. It is dedicated to the 580 members of New York's 7th Regiment, 107th Infantry,
who gave their lives in the World War.
9/29/1927

Central Park: W.P.A. employees removing the 86th Street, crosstown car tracks that were laid on a transverse vehicular road through the Park.
